r=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/30/01 5:32:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  What's your favourite Nuclear Rocket Concept?</span><hr size=1> My name says it for me. Second favourite would be NERVA ofcourse. Bestonnet got me interested in that program. Twice the thrust of chemical and a fraction of the fuel mass. They must have had fun building and testing all those then state of the art reactor rockets back in the 70's. Some interesting names to them. I wonder who picked PEEWEE.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 2/12/02 7:48:37 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/30/01 6:12:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What's your favourite Nuclear Rocket Concept?</span><hr size=1> Orion is the best nuclear rocket concept.<br>
<br>
If I had to choose a second best it would be fission fragment because it gets about the same performance as Orion (probably better) without any nuclear rapid criticality devices. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/30/01 6:58:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What's your favourite Nuclear Rocket Concept?</span><hr size=1> Definitely Orion.  The main reason for me is that it's buildable with<br>
1960's technology.  Maybe the Chinese are the most likely candidate<br>
for building a nuclear pulse rocket today. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/30/01 7:29:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What's your favourite Nuclear Rocket Concept?</span><hr size=1> Found more info about fission fragment reactor here:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.spaceflightnow.com/news/n0101/19marsnuclear/">www.spaceflightnow.com/ne...rsnuclear/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
In the article the lead scientist states that velocity of 80kps would<br>
be attainable...<br>
<br>
Question:  Do you think he meant the exhaust velocity, or the<br>
vehicle's velocity?  I have read that an Orion would be capable, at<br>
most 10% the speed of light... which is considerably faster than 80<br>
kps (30,000 kps give or take)??? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/30/01 9:11:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Has to be Orion</span><hr size=1> I have to go with Orion, for its simplicity and vast lifting power. Any nuclear application in space will provoke a maximum effort from the pop-culture paranoids of the antinuclear movement. Relative magnitude means nothing to these people. A very small NERVA upper stage would have them up in arms as much as a 10,000 ton Orion. If you have to fight this battle anyway, you might as well go for the maximum benefit.<br>
For this reason, if someone decides to go nuclear, they will almost certainly go for the most powerful system that is technically and economically feasible. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/udrcarstairs.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/1/01 1:04:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.angelfire.com/rant/AVitW/images/bioh.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Orion - by far </span><hr size=1> Mainly because it can be done NOW, with no new technologies or materials needed. Oh, we will have to toy with it to get the right materials, the correct yields, etc - but these are merely refinements of existing technologies. No zero-point energy, cold fusion, super tensile strength materials, precision fission-free fusion detonations – no theoretical or mythical technologies required.<br>
<br>
All that is required is the determination and the guts.  <br>
<br>
